the word &#39;form&#39; in your translation.\n\nThis verse can be seen as the synthesis of all vedanta philosophies in a\nunifying way.\n\nGod is three-fold. (1) ajaH -- he is that entity which is unborn, because\nbrahman is beyond birth. (2) avyayAtmA -- he is the unchanging consciousness\nwhich underlies this manifest world that appears in front of us. (3)\nbhUtAnAm IshvaraH -- he is the personal Lord whom we can interact with in\nthis world that appears in front of us.\n\nAll three of these may appear contradictory to each other, but they are also\nsimultaneously true. How is this possible? Because of the nature of\nAtma-mAyA.\n\nPutting the verse in context, Krishna is simply trying to answer Arjuna&#39;s\nprevious question and explain that he is not an ordinary person. He is\ntimeless, but takes &#39;birth&#39; every now and again. This birth is not the\nresult of dharma and adharma, or punya and papa. He is not controlled by\nmaya or karma or the three gunas. Even in his avatara-form, he is the\nsupreme lord himself. As a result, though he may take &#39;birth&#39;, he has\nknowledge of all events of the past and future.\n\nBeautiful verse.\n\nsasneham,\n\n   ajit\n\n\n\n\n\nOn Tue, Jul 26, 2011 at 6:45 AM, Murahari Vadapalli &lt;murahariv@...&gt;wrote:\n\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; Namaste All,\n&gt;\n&gt; Your help in understanding this verse is greatly appreciated.\n&gt;\n&gt; ajo pi sann avyayatma bhtanam isvaro pi san\n&gt; prakrtim svam adhisthaya sambhavamy atma-mayaya\n&gt;\n&gt; Translation: Although being birthless, imperishable and immmutable, The\n&gt; Lord of all living entities; being so situated I appear in this world in *my\n&gt; original transcedental &quot;FORM&quot;* by my internal potency\n&gt;\n&gt; This verse is very confusing to me because my understanding is as follows:\n&gt; a) It is due to the sound, the form and name are created and that&#39;s why it\n&gt; is said that world is with names and forms\n&gt;\n&gt; How to reconcile this verse with vedas and upanishadic scriptures that talk\n&gt; about nirakara brahman? Why is bhagavan talking about form here?\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; Thanks & Regards,\n&gt; --Murahari\n&gt;\n&gt;\n\r\n--bcaec520eb07221fa304a8fc403f\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;div&gt;Dear Murahari,&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&#39;prakriti&#39; is a difficu=\r\nlt word to translate, because it has many shades of meaning. &#39;svAm prak=\r\nRtim&#39; can be translated as &#39;my form&#39; or &#39;my nature&#39;. Th=\r\ne &#39;form&#39; of a cow is &#39;cow-form&#39;. The &#39;form&#39; of a pe=\r\nrson is &#39;person-form&#39;. Similarly, the &#39;form&#39; of the formles=\r\ns is &#39;formless-form&#39; :-) i.e. don&#39;t get trapped by the use of t=\r\nhe word &#39;form&#39; in=A0your translation.&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Thi=\r\ns verse can be seen as the synthesis of all vedanta philosophies in a unify=\r\ning way. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;God is three-fold. (1) ajaH --=A0he is=A0=\r\nthat entity which is unborn, because brahman is beyond birth. (2) avyayAtmA=\r\n --=A0he is=A0the unchanging consciousness which underlies this manifest wo=\r\nrld that appears in front of us. (3) bhUtAnAm IshvaraH --=A0he is=A0the per=\r\nsonal Lord whom we can interact with in this world that appears in front of=\r\n us.&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;All three of these may appear contradictory =\r\nto each other, but they are also simultaneously true. How is this possible?=\r\n Because of the nature of Atma-mAyA.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Putting the ve=\r\nrse=A0in context, Krishna is simply trying to answer Arjuna&#39;s previous =\r\nquestion and explain that he is not an ordinary person. He is timeless, but=\r\n takes &#39;birth&#39; every now and again.=A0This birth=A0is not the resul=\r\nt of dharma and adharma, or punya a